                "who invented television": ["Television technology first developed in the nineteenth century, when the German Ferdinand Braun invented the cathode ray tube in 1897 AD, and the cathode ray tube was first used to produce images in 1907 AD. This was followed by independent developments by the Englishman Philo Farnsworth and the Russian Vladimir Zworykin. In the 1920s, the Scotsman John Logie Baird patented the idea of ​​using a set of transparent rods to transmit television images. Baird was the first person to display moving images on television. As for electronic television, it was invented by the American Philo Farnsworth in 1927 AD, where he used a vacuum tube to produce images electronically on a light-sensitive screen. In 1900 AD, the word ,television, appeared for the first time at the Paris Exhibition by the Frenchman Constantin Persky.",],

"inventor of television": ["Television technology first developed in the nineteenth century, when the German Ferdinand Braun invented the cathode ray tube in 1897 The cathode ray tube was first used to produce images in 1907. This was followed by independent developments by the Englishman Philo Farnsworth and the Russian Vladimir Zworykin. In the 1920s, the Scotsman John Logie Baird patented the idea of ​​using a set of transparent rods to transmit television images. Baird was the first person to display moving pictures on television. The electronic television was invented by the American Philo Farnsworth in 1927, where he used a vacuum tube to produce images electronically on a light-sensitive screen. In 1900, the word ,television, first appeared at the Paris Exhibition by the Frenchman Constantin Persky.",],


